Generalized first definition in `Mathlib.Analysis.NormedSpace.Extend`, and used this to prove `RCLike` generalizations of Hahn-Banach separation theorems.

Co-authored-by: Jireh Loreaux <loreaujy@gmail.com>

```suggestion
variable [AddCommGroup F] [Module ‚Ñù F] [Module ùïú F] [IsScalarTower ‚Ñù ùïú F]
```
Why this change?
The linter spotted that the typeclass assumptions weren't needed, and it turns out that it was right.
Oh wait, I see...this was the style linter. Let me revert that...
This should be a lemma, possibly generated by `@[simps]` on the definition
Tried @[simps] on the definition, and it fails, suggesting @[simps!]. When I tried that, it broke the definition and several things below.

By the way, though, if I give the definition `@[simp]` this works. Is that an ok change? This feels very different than `@[simps]`, though so I am wary of it. Wouldn't this be marking the definition itself as a simp lemma?
No, if `@[simps]` doesn't generate the lemma you want, you can just forget about it and do it by hand, i.e. what is already there.

Actually, I just tried @[simps!] again, and it didn't break this time...and I have no idea why. I noticed that this generates a longer list of lemmas to apply in the call than if I stick with the single lemma I introduced. Is it better to use the auto generated lemmas if it leads to using more rewrites or is it better to introduce the new lemma. Thanks again!
You can use `@[simps!?]` or `@[simps?]` to make it tell you what lemmas it generated. In this case, I think the one you wrote by hand is better.
Cool. I rolled those changes back.
I think this should be called `re_LinToùïú'` or `re_linToùïú'`

```suggestion
    sub_self, sub_zero]
```
I don't think there's a need to put multiple tactics on a line here or below
Maybe these should go into the RCLike namespace
If they're in the `RCLike` namespace, then there is no reason to append `RCLike` to the names of the lemmas.

Interesting. What is the better style move, here? Should I just remove the `RCLike` from the names of the lemmas and put these (named identically) lemmas, or should I keep them out of the namespace and include the underscored qualification? (I imagine this is sorted by the naming convention somehow, but I'm still internalizing this...)

By the way, I tried removing the `_RCLike` from these names, but Lean then is still identifying the results with those named identically (aside from the `RCLike.` appearing above...the results these were based on and use.) I get structural recursion errors. I can add `_root_` to fix this, I guess...

Those errors come from the fact that what you invoke (say) `geometric_hahn_banach_open` from `RCLike.geometric_hahn_banach_open`, it looks like a recursive call. To make sure that Lean interprets it as invoking the original theorem, you can write `_root_.geometric_hahn_banach_open` to specify you want the one from the root namespace.

As for whether we want the lemmas in the `RCLike` namespace or with `rclike` appended to the names (it should probably be spelled like that in this case), I don't really have a strong preference.
Yes. That worked. This is much better. Thanks to you both!

Probably this works:
```suggestion
  simp only [real_of_LinToùïú', exists_and_left]
  exact ‚ü®u, h1‚ü©
```
or this:
```suggestion
  simp only [real_of_LinToùïú', exists_and_left]
  exact ‚ü®u, h1.1, h1.2‚ü©
```
Somewhat irritatingly, neither works. (This is probably due to that second existential quantifier!)
Thanks, by the way, for looking over this!!
`exact ‚ü®u, h1.1, v, h1.2‚ü©` does the job!

```suggestion
  exact ((hxy.trans_lt (hlA y hy)).trans hl).false
```

```suggestion
/--Real linear extension of continuous extension of `LinearMap.extendToùïú'` -/
noncomputable def extendToùïú'‚Çó : (E ‚ÜíL[‚Ñù] ‚Ñù) ‚Üí‚Çó[‚Ñù] (E ‚ÜíL[ùïú] ùïú) :=
```
As it stands, `LinToùïú'` doesn't follow the [naming convention](https://leanprover-community.github.io/contribute/naming.html): it should be in lowerCamelCase, i.e. `linToùïú'`. But it's probably better to make it a variation of `extendToùïú'`, analogously to `inner‚Çó`.
Excellent, thanks!

```suggestion
@[simp]
lemma re_extendToùïú'‚Çó (g : E ‚ÜíL[‚Ñù] ‚Ñù) (x : E) :  re ((LinToùïú' g) x : ùïú) = g x := by
```
We usually want to stick to the actual name of the function that is being referred to, i.e. `re` in this case.
